# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smart-grid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:smart-grid/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Utilities may signal demand requests to their customers in a variety of ways, including simple off-peak metering, in which power is cheaper at certain times of the day, and smart metering, in which explicit requests or changes in price can be communicated to customers.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The customer may adjust power demand by postponing some tasks that require large amounts of electric power, or may decide to pay a higher price for their electricity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some customers may switch part of their consumption to alternate sources, such as on-site solar panels and batteries.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In many respects, demand response can be put simply as a technology-enabled economic rationing system for electric power supply.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In demand response, voluntary rationing is accomplished by price incentives—offering lower net unit pricing in exchange for reduced power consumption in peak periods.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The direct implication is that users of electric power capacity not reducing usage (load) during peak periods will pay "surge" unit prices, whether directly, or factored into general rates.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Involuntary rationing, if employed, would be accomplished via rolling blackouts during peak load periods.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Practically speaking, summer heat waves and winter deep freezes might be characterized by planned power outages for consumers and businesses if voluntary rationing via incentives fails to reduce load adequately to match total power supply.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In 2013, it was expected that demand response programs will be designed to decrease electricity consumption or shift it from on-peak to off-peak periods depending on consumers' preferences and lifestyles.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In 2016 demand response was defined as "a wide range of actions which can be taken at the customer side of the electricity meter in response to particular conditions within the electricity system such as peak period network congestion or high prices".
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In 2010, demand response was defined as a reduction in demand designed to reduce peak demand or avoid system emergencies.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] It can be a more cost-effective alternative than adding generation capabilities to meet the peak and occasional demand spikes.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The underlying objective of DR is to actively engage customers in modifying their consumption in response to pricing signals.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The goal is to reflect supply expectations through consumer price signals or controls and enable dynamic changes in consumption relative to price.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In electricity grids, DR is similar to dynamic demand mechanisms to manage customer consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to market prices.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The difference is that demand response mechanisms respond to explicit requests to shut off, whereas dynamic demand devices passively shut off when stress in the grid is sensed.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Demand response can involve actually curtailing power used or by starting on-site generation which may or may not be connected in parallel with the grid.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] This is a quite different concept from energy efficiency, which means using less power to perform the same tasks, on a continuous basis or whenever that task is performed.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] At the same time, demand response is a component of smart energy demand, which also includes energy efficiency, home and building energy management, distributed renewable resources, and electric vehicle charging.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Current demand response schemes are implemented with large and small commercial as well as residential customers, often through the use of dedicated control systems to shed loads in response to a request by a utility or market price conditions.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Services (lights, machines, air conditioning) are reduced according to a preplanned load prioritization scheme during the critical time frames.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] An alternative to load shedding is on-site generation of electricity to supplement the power grid.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Under conditions of tight electricity supply, demand response can significantly decrease the peak price and, in general, electricity price volatility.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Demand response is generally used to refer to mechanisms used to encourage consumers to reduce demand, thereby reducing the peak demand for electricity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Since electrical generation and transmission systems are generally sized to correspond to peak demand (plus margin for forecasting error and unforeseen events), lowering peak demand reduces overall plant and capital cost requirements.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Depending on the configuration of generation capacity, however, demand response may also be used to increase demand (load) at times of high production and low demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some systems may thereby encourage energy storage to arbitrage between periods of low and high demand (or low and high prices).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is an electricity intensive process to convert computer hardware infrastructure, software skills and electricity into electronic currency.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is used to increase the demand during surplus hours by consuming cheaper power.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] There are three types of demand response - emergency demand response, economic demand response and ancillary services demand response.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Emergency demand response is employed to avoid involuntary service interruptions during times of supply scarcity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Economic demand response is employed to allow electricity customers to curtail their consumption when the productivity or convenience of consuming that electricity is worth less to them than paying for the electricity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Ancillary services demand response consists of a number of specialty services that are needed to ensure the secure operation of the transmission grid and which have traditionally been provided by generators.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In most electric power systems, some or all consumers pay a fixed price per unit of electricity independent of the cost of production at the time of consumption.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The consumer price may be established by the government or a regulator, and typically represents an average cost per unit of production over a given timeframe (for example, a year).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Consumption therefore is not sensitive to the cost of production in the short term (e.g. on an hourly basis).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] A pure economist might extrapolate the concept to hypothesize that consumers served under these fixed-rate tariffs are endowed with theoretical "call options" on electricity, though in reality, like any other business, the customer is simply buying what is on offer at the agreed price.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] A customer in a department store buying a $10 item at 9.00 am might notice 10 sales staff on the floor but only one occupied serving him or her, while at 3.00 pm the customer could buy the same $10 article and notice all 10 sales staff occupied.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In virtually all power systems electricity is produced by generators that are dispatched in merit order, i.e., generators with the lowest marginal cost (lowest variable cost of production) are used first, followed by the next cheapest, etc., until the instantaneous electricity demand is satisfied.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In most power systems the wholesale price of electricity will be equal to the marginal cost of the highest cost generator that is injecting energy, which will vary with the level of demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Thus the variation in pricing can be significant: for example, in Ontario between August and September 2006, wholesale prices (in Canadian Dollars) paid to producers ranged from a peak of $318 per MW·h to a minimum of - (negative) $3.10 per MW·h.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] It is not unusual for the price to vary by a factor of two to five due to the daily demand cycle.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] A negative price indicates that producers were being charged to provide electricity to the grid (and consumers paying real-time pricing may have actually received a rebate for consuming electricity during this period).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] This generally occurs at night when demand falls to a level where all generators are operating at their minimum output levels and some of them must be shut down.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The negative price is the inducement to bring about these shutdowns in a least-cost manner.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The latter study found that even small shifts in peak demand would have a large effect on savings to consumers and avoided costs for additional peak capacity: a 1% shift in peak demand would result in savings of 3.9%, billions of dollars at the system level.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] An approximately 10% reduction in peak demand (achievable depending on the elasticity of demand) would result in systems savings of between $8 and $28 billion.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] While the net benefits would be significantly less than the claimed $35 billion, they would still be quite substantial.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In Ontario, Canada, the Independent Electricity System Operator has noted that in 2006, peak demand exceeded 25,000 megawatts during only 32 system hours (less than 0.4% of the time), while maximum demand during the year was just over 27,000 megawatts.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The ability to "shave" peak demand based on reliable commitments would therefore allow the province to reduce built capacity by approximately 2,000 megawatts.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In an electricity grid, electricity consumption and production must balance at all times; any significant imbalance could cause grid instability or severe voltage fluctuations, and cause failures within the grid.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Total generation capacity is therefore sized to correspond to total peak demand with some margin of error and allowance for contingencies (such as plants being off-line during peak demand periods).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Operators will generally plan to use the least expensive generating capacity (in terms of marginal cost) at any given period, and use additional capacity from more expensive plants as demand increases.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Demand response in most cases is targeted at reducing peak demand to reduce the risk of potential disturbances, avoid additional capital cost requirements for additional plants, and avoid use of more expensive or less efficient operating plants.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Consumers of electricity will also pay higher prices if generation capacity is used from a higher-cost source of power generation.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Demand response may also be used to increase demand during periods of high supply and low demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some types of generating plant must be run at close to full capacity (such as nuclear), while other types may produce at negligible marginal cost (such as wind and solar).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Since there is usually limited capacity to store energy, demand response may attempt to increase load during these periods to maintain grid stability.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] For example, in the province of Ontario in September 2006, there was a short period of time when electricity prices were negative for certain users.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Energy storage such as pumped-storage hydroelectricity is a way to increase load during periods of low demand for use during later periods.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Use of demand response to increase load is less common, but may be necessary or efficient in systems where there are large amounts of generating capacity that cannot be easily cycled down.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some grids may use pricing mechanisms that are not real-time, but easier to implement (users pay higher prices during the day and lower prices at night, for example) to provide some of the benefits of the demand response mechanism with less demanding technological requirements.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In the UK, Economy 7 and similar schemes that attempt to shift demand associated with electric heating to overnight off-peak periods have been in operation since the 1970s.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] More recently, in 2006 Ontario began implementing a "smart meter" program that implements "time-of-use" (TOU) pricing, which tiers pricing according to on-peak, mid-peak and off-peak schedules.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] During the winter, on-peak is defined as morning and early evening, mid-peak as midday to late afternoon, and off-peak as nighttime; during the summer, the on-peak and mid-peak periods are reversed, reflecting air conditioning as the driver of summer demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] As of May 1, 2015, most Ontario electrical utilities have completed converting all customers to "smart meter" time-of-use billing with on-peak rates about 200% and mid-peak rates about 150% of the off-peak rate per kWh.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Australia has national standards for Demand Response (AS/NZS 4755 series), which has been implemented nationwide by electricity distributors for several decades, e.g. controlling storage water heaters, air conditioners and pool pumps.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In 2016, how to manage electrical energy storage (e.g., batteries) has been added into the series of standards.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Energy consumers need some incentive to respond to such a request from a demand response provider.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Demand response incentives can be formal or informal.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The utility might create a tariff-based incentive by passing along short-term increases in the price of electricity, or they might impose mandatory cutbacks during a heat wave for selected high-volume users, who are compensated for their participation.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Other users may receive a rebate or other incentive based on firm commitments to reduce power during periods of high demand, sometimes referred to as *negawatts* (the term was coined by Amory Lovins in 1985).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] For example, California introduced its own ELRP, where upon an emergency declaration enrolled customers get a credit for lowering their electricity use ($1 per kWh in 2021, $2 in 2022).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Commercial and industrial power users might impose load shedding on themselves, without a request from the utility.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some businesses generate their own power and wish to stay within their energy production capacity to avoid buying power from the grid.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some utilities have commercial tariff structures that set a customer's power costs for the month based on the customer's moment of highest use, or peak demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] This encourages users to flatten their demand for energy, known as energy demand management, which sometimes requires cutting back services temporarily.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Smart metering has been implemented in some jurisdictions to provide real-time pricing for all types of users, as opposed to fixed-rate pricing throughout the demand period.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In this application, users have a direct incentive to reduce their use at high-demand, high-price periods.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Many users may not be able to effectively reduce their demand at various times, or the peak prices may be lower than the level required to induce a change in demand during short time periods (users have low price sensitivity, or elasticity of demand is low).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Automated control systems exist, which, although effective, may be too expensive to be feasible for some applications.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Smart grid applications improve the ability of electricity producers and consumers to communicate with one another and make decisions about how and when to produce and consume electrical power.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] This emerging technology will allow customers to shift from an event-based demand response where the utility requests the shedding of load, towards a more 24/7-based demand response where the customer sees incentives for controlling load all the time.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Although this back-and-forth dialogue increases the opportunities for demand response, customers are still largely influenced by economic incentives and are reluctant to relinquish total control of their assets to utility companies.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] One advantage of a smart grid application is time-based pricing.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Customers who traditionally pay a fixed rate for consumed energy (kWh) and requested peak load can set their threshold and adjust their usage to take advantage of fluctuating prices.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] This may require the use of an energy management system to control appliances and equipment and can involve economies of scale.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Another advantage, mainly for large customers with generation, is being able to closely monitor, shift, and balance load in a way that allows the customer to save peak load and not only save on kWh and kW/month but be able to trade what they have saved in an energy market.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Again, this involves sophisticated energy management systems, incentives, and a viable trading market.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Smart grid applications increase the opportunities for demand response by providing real time data to producers and consumers, but the economic and environmental incentives remain the driving force behind the practice.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] One of the most important means of demand response in the future smart grids is electric vehicles.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Aggregation of this new source of energy, which is also a new source of uncertainty in the electrical systems, is critical to preserving the stability and quality of smart grids, consequently, the electric vehicle parking lots can be considered a demand response aggregation entity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The modern power grid is making a transition from the traditional vertically integrated utility structures to distributed systems as it begins to integrate higher penetrations of renewable energy generation.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] These sources of energy are often diffusely distributed and intermittent by nature.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] These features introduce problems in grid stability and efficiency which lead to limitations on the amount of these resources which can be effectively added to the grid.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In a traditional vertically integrated grid, energy is provided by utility generators which are able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Generation output by renewable resources is governed by environmental conditions and is generally not able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Responsive control over noncritical loads that are connected to the grid has been shown to be an effective strategy able to mitigate undesirable fluctuations introduced by these renewable resources.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In this way instead of the generation responding to changes in demand, the demand responds to changes in generation.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In order to implement demand response systems, coordination of large numbers of distributed resources through sensors, actuators, and communications protocols becomes necessary.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] To be effective, the devices need to be economical, robust, and yet still effective at managing their tasks of control.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In addition, effective control requires a strong capability to coordinate large networks of devices, managing and optimizing these distributed systems from both an economic and a security standpoint.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In addition, the increased presence of variable renewable generation drives a greater need for authorities to procure more ancillary services for grid balance.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] One of these services is contingency reserve, which is used to regulate the grid frequency in contingencies.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] As the ratio of inverter-based generation compared to conventional generation increases, the mechanical inertia used to stabilize frequency decreases.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] When coupled with the sensitivity of inverter-based generation to transient frequencies, the provision of ancillary services from other sources than generators becomes increasingly important.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Technologies are available, and more are under development, to automate the process of demand response.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Such technologies detect the need for load shedding, communicate the demand to participating users, automate load shedding, and verify compliance with demand-response programs.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] GridWise and EnergyWeb are two major federal initiatives in the United States to develop these technologies.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Universities and private industry are also doing research and development in this arena.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Scalable and comprehensive software solutions for DR enable business and industry growth.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some utilities are considering and testing automated systems connected to industrial, commercial and residential users that can reduce consumption at times of peak demand, essentially delaying draw marginally.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Although the amount of demand delayed may be small, the implications for the grid (including financial) may be substantial, since system stability planning often involves building capacity for extreme peak demand events, plus a margin of safety in reserve.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Such events may only occur a few times per year.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The process may involve turning down or off certain appliances or sinks (and, when demand is unexpectedly low, potentially increasing usage).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] For example, heating may be turned down or air conditioning or refrigeration may be turned up (turning up to a higher temperature uses less electricity), delaying slightly the draw until a peak in usage has passed.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Although this is an experimental program, at scale these solutions have the potential to reduce peak demand considerably.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The success of such programs depends on the development of appropriate technology, a suitable pricing system for electricity, and the cost of the underlying technology.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Bonneville Power experimented with direct-control technologies in Washington and Oregon residences, and found that the avoided transmission investment would justify the cost of the technology.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Other methods to implementing demand response approach the issue of subtly reducing duty cycles rather than implementing thermostat setbacks.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] These can be implemented using customized building automation systems programming, or through swarm-logic methods coordinating multiple loads in a facility (e.g.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Similar approach can be implemented for managing air conditioning peak demand in summer peak regions.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Pre-cooling or maintaining slightly higher thermostat setting can help with the peak demand reduction.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In 2008 it was announced that electric refrigerators will be sold in the UK sensing dynamic demand which will delay or advance the cooling cycle based on monitoring grid frequency but they are not readily available as of 2018.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Industrial customers are also providing demand response.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified demand response resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term nega-battery.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The selection of suitable industries for demand response provision is typically based on an assessment of the so-called value of lost load.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Some data centers are located far apart for redundancy and can migrate loads between them, while also performing demand response.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Shedding loads during peak demand is important because it reduces the need for new power plants.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] To respond to high peak demand, utilities build very capital-intensive power plants and lines.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Peak demand happens just a few times a year, so those assets run at a mere fraction of their capacity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Electric users pay for this idle capacity through the prices they pay for electricity.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] According to the Demand Response Smart Grid Coalition, 10%–20% of electricity costs in the United States are due to peak demand during only 100 hours of the year.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] DR is a way for utilities to reduce the need for large capital expenditures, and thus keep rates lower overall; however, there is an economic limit to such reductions because consumers lose the productive or convenience value of the electricity not consumed.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Thus, it is misleading to only look at the cost savings that demand response can produce without also considering what the consumer gives up in the process.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] It is estimated that a 5% lowering of demand would have resulted in a 50% price reduction during the peak hours of the California electricity crisis in 2000–2001.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] With consumers facing peak pricing and reducing their demand, the market should become more resilient to intentional withdrawal of offers from the supply side.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Residential and commercial electricity use often vary drastically during the day, and demand response attempts to reduce the variability based on pricing signals.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Electric systems and grids typically scale total potential production to meet projected peak demand (with sufficient spare capacity to deal with unanticipated events).
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] By "smoothing" demand to reduce peaks, less investment in operational reserve will be required, and existing facilities will operate more frequently.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] In addition, significant peaks may only occur rarely, such as two or three times per year, requiring significant capital investments to meet infrequent events.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The report estimates that in 2004 potential demand response capability equaled about 20,500 megawatts (MW), 3% of total U.S. peak demand, while actual delivered peak demand reduction was about 9,000 MW (1.3% of peak), leaving ample margin for improvement.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] It is further estimated that load management capability has fallen by 32% since 1996.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Factors affecting this trend include fewer utilities offering load management services, declining enrollment in existing programs, the changing role and responsibility of utilities, and changing supply/demand balance.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] To encourage the use and implementation of demand response in the United States, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] 745 in March 2011, which requires a certain level of compensation for providers of economic demand response that participate in wholesale power markets.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] The order is highly controversial and has been opposed by a number of energy economists, including Professor William W.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Hogan at Harvard University's Kennedy School.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Professor Hogan asserts that the order overcompensates providers of demand response, thereby encouraging the curtailment of electricity whose economic value exceeds the cost of producing it.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Professor Hogan further asserts that Order No.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] 745 is anticompetitive and amounts to "...an application of regulatory authority to enforce a buyer's cartel." Several affected parties, including the State of California, have filed suit in federal court challenging the legality of Order 745.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] A debate regarding the economic efficiency and fairness of Order 745 appeared in a series of articles published in The Electricity Journal.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated Order 745 in its entirety.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Whether the Court of Appeals erred in holding that the rule issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is arbitrary and capricious.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] On January 25, 2016, the United States Supreme Court in a 6-2 decision in *FERC v.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Electric Power Supply Ass'n* concluded that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acted within its authority to ensure "just and reasonable" rates in the wholesale energy market.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] 2222 on September 17, 2020, enabling distributed energy resources to participate in regional wholesale electricity markets.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Market operators submitted initial compliance plans by early 2022.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] As of December 2009 National Grid had 2369 MW contracted to provide demand response, known as STOR, the demand side provides 839 MW (35%) from 89 sites.
[src:smart-grid/demand-response] Of this 839 MW approximately 750 MW is back-up generation with the remaining being load reduction.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Conventional power stations, such as coal-fired, gas, and nuclear powered plants, as well as hydroelectric dams and large-scale solar power stations, are centralized and often require electric energy to be transmitted over long distances.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] By contrast, DER systems are decentralized, modular, and more flexible technologies that are located close to the load they serve, albeit having capacities of only 10 megawatts (MW) or less.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] These systems can comprise multiple generation and storage components; in this instance, they are referred to as hybrid power systems.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] DER systems typically use renewable energy sources, including small hydro, biomass, biogas, solar power, wind power, and geothermal power, and increasingly play an important role for the electric power distribution system.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A grid-connected device for electricity storage can also be classified as a DER system and is often called a **distributed energy storage system** (**DESS**).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] By means of an interface, DER systems can be managed and coordinated within a smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed generation and storage enables the collection of energy from many sources and may lower environmental impacts and improve the security of supply.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] One of the major issues with the integration of the DER such as solar power, wind power, etc. is the uncertain nature of such electricity resources.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Microgrids are modern, localized, small-scale grids, contrary to the traditional, centralized electricity grid (macrogrid).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Microgrids can disconnect from the centralized grid and operate autonomously, strengthen grid resilience, and help mitigate grid disturbances.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] They are typically low-voltage AC grids, often use diesel generators, and are installed by the community they serve.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Microgrids increasingly employ a mixture of different distributed energy resources, such as solar hybrid power systems, which significantly reduce the amount of carbon emitted.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Historically, central plants have been an integral part of the electric grid, in which large generating facilities are specifically located either close to resources or otherwise located far from populated load centers.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] These, in turn, supply the traditional transmission and distribution (T&D) grid that distributes bulk power to load centers and from there to consumers.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] These were developed when the costs of transporting fuel and integrating generating technologies into populated areas far exceeded the cost of developing T&D facilities and tariffs.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Central plants are usually designed to take advantage of available economies of scale in a site-specific manner, and are built as "one-off", custom projects.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Thus, the grid had become the main driver of remote customers' power costs and power quality problems, which became more acute as digital equipment required extremely reliable electricity.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Efficiency gains no longer come from increasing generating capacity, but from smaller units located closer to sites of demand.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] For example, coal power plants are built away from cities to prevent their heavy air pollution from affecting the populace.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In addition, such plants are often built near collieries to minimize the cost of transporting coal.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Hydroelectric plants are by their nature limited to operating at sites with sufficient water flow.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Low pollution is a crucial advantage of combined cycle plants that burn natural gas.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The low pollution permits the plants to be near enough to a city to provide district heating and cooling.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed energy resources are mass-produced, small, and less site-specific.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Along with higher relative prices for energy, higher overall complexity and total costs for regulatory oversight, tariff administration, and metering and billing.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Capital markets have come to realize that right-sized resources, for individual customers, distribution substations, or microgrids, are able to offer important but little-known economic advantages over central plants.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Smaller units achieved greater economic benefits through mass-production than larger units gained from their size alone.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The increased value of these resources—resulting from improvements in financial risk, engineering flexibility, security, and environmental quality—often outweighs their apparent cost disadvantages.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed generation (DG), vis-à-vis central plants, must be justified on a life-cycle basis.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Unfortunately, many of the direct, and virtually all of the indirect, benefits of DG are not captured within traditional utility cash-flow accounting.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] While the levelized cost of DG is typically more expensive than conventional, centralized sources on a kilowatt-hour basis, this does not consider negative aspects of conventional fuels.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The additional premium for DG is rapidly declining as demand increases and technology progresses, and sufficient and reliable demand may bring economies of scale, innovation, competition, and more flexible financing, that could make DG clean energy part of a more diversified future.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] DG reduces the amount of energy lost in transmitting electricity because the electricity is generated very near where it is used, perhaps even in the same building.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This also reduces the size and number of power lines that must be constructed.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Typical DER systems in a feed-in tariff (FIT) scheme have low maintenance, low pollution and high efficiencies.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In the past, these traits required dedicated operating engineers and large complex plants to reduce pollution.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] However, modern embedded systems can provide these traits with automated operation and renewable energy, such as solar, wind and geothermal.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This reduces the size of power plant that can show a profit.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In November 2024 Deye and Sol-Ark inverter manufacturer remotely disabled in some countries due to alleged regional sales policy dispute.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The companies later claimed the blockage was not remote but due to geofencing mechanisms built into the inverters.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] EU NIS2 directive expands the cybersecurity requirements to the energy generation market, which has faced backlash from renewable energy lobby groups.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Grid parity occurs when an alternative energy source can generate electricity at a levelized cost (LCOE) that is less than or equal to the end consumer's retail price.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Reaching grid parity is considered to be the point at which an energy source becomes a contender for widespread development without subsidies or government support.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Since the 2010s, grid parity for solar and wind has become a reality in a growing number of markets, including Australia, several European countries, and some states in the U.S.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed energy resource (**DER**) systems are small-scale power generation or storage technologies (typically in the range of 1 kW to 10,000 kW) used to provide an alternative to or an enhancement of the traditional electric power system.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] DER systems typically are characterized by high initial capital costs per kilowatt.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] DER systems also serve as storage device and are often called *Distributed energy storage systems* (DESS).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed cogeneration sources use steam turbines, natural gas-fired fuel cells, microturbines or reciprocating engines to turn generators.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The hot exhaust is then used for space or water heating, or to drive an absorptive chiller for cooling such as air-conditioning.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In addition to natural gas-based schemes, distributed energy projects can also include other renewable or low carbon fuels including biofuels, biogas, landfill gas, sewage gas, coal bed methane, syngas and associated petroleum gas.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Delta-ee consultants stated in 2013 that with 64% of global sales, the fuel cell micro combined heat and power passed the conventional systems in sales in 2012.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] 20.000 units were sold in Japan in 2012 overall within the Ene Farm project.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] With a Lifetime of around 60,000 hours for PEM fuel cell units, which shut down at night, this equates to an estimated lifetime of between ten and fifteen years.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] For a price of $22,600 before installation.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] For 2013 a state subsidy for 50,000 units is in place.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In addition, molten carbonate fuel cell and solid oxide fuel cells using natural gas, such as the ones from FuelCell Energy and the Bloom energy server, or waste-to-energy processes such as the Gate 5 Energy System are used as a distributed energy resource.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Photovoltaics uses solar cells assembled into solar panels to convert sunlight into electricity.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] It is a growing technology, doubling its worldwide installed capacity every couple of years.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] PV systems range from distributed, residential, and commercial rooftop or building integrated installations, to large, centralized utility-scale photovoltaic power stations.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The predominant PV technology is crystalline silicon, while thin-film solar cell technology accounts for about 10 percent of global photovoltaic deployment.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In recent years, PV technology has improved its sunlight to electricity conversion efficiency, reduced the installation cost per watt as well as its energy payback time (EPBT) and levelised cost of electricity (LCOE), and has reached grid parity in at least 19 different markets in 2014.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] As most renewable energy sources and unlike coal and nuclear, solar PV is variable and non-dispatchable, but has no fuel costs, operating pollution, as well as greatly reduced mining-safety and operating-safety issues.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] It produces peak power around local noon each day and its capacity factor is around 20 percent.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Wind turbines can be distributed energy resources or they can be built at utility scale.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] These have low maintenance and low pollution, but distributed wind unlike utility-scale wind has much higher costs than other sources of energy.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] As with solar, wind energy is variable and non-dispatchable.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Wind towers and generators have substantial insurable liabilities caused by high winds, but good operating safety.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed generation from wind hybrid power systems combines wind power with other DER systems.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] One such example is the integration of wind turbines into solar hybrid power systems, as wind tends to complement solar because the peak operating times for each system occur at different times of the day and year.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Hydroelectricity is the most widely used form of renewable energy and its potential has already been explored to a large extent or is compromised due to issues such as environmental impacts on fisheries, and increased demand for recreational access.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] However, using modern 21st century technology, such as wave power, can make large amounts of new hydropower capacity available, with minor environmental impact.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Modular and scalable *Next generation kinetic energy turbines* can be deployed in arrays to serve the needs on a residential, commercial, industrial, municipal or even regional scale.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] *Microhydro kinetic generators* neither require dams nor impoundments, as they utilize the kinetic energy of water motion, either waves or flow.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] No construction is needed on the shoreline or sea bed, which minimizes environmental impacts to habitats and simplifies the permitting process.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Such power generation also has minimal environmental impact and non-traditional microhydro applications can be tethered to existing construction such as docks, piers, bridge abutments, or similar structures.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Municipal solid waste (MSW) and natural waste, such as sewage sludge, food waste and animal manure will decompose and discharge methane-containing gas that can be collected and used as fuel in gas turbines or micro turbines to produce electricity as a distributed energy resource.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Additionally, a California-based company, Gate 5 Energy Partners, Inc. has developed a process that transforms natural waste materials, such as sewage sludge, into biofuel that can be combusted to power a steam turbine that produces power.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This power can be used in lieu of grid-power at the waste source (such as a treatment plant, farm or dairy).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A distributed energy resource is not limited to the generation of electricity but may also include a device to store distributed energy (DE).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Distributed energy storage systems (DESS) applications include several types of battery, pumped hydro, compressed air, and thermal energy storage.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Access to energy storage for commercial applications is easily accessible through programs such as energy storage as a service (ESaaS).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Compared to the other types, lead-acid batteries have a shorter lifetime and lower energy density.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] (4–6% per year) as well as low investment and maintenance costs, they are currently the predominant technology used in small-scale, residential PV systems, as lithium-ion batteries are still being developed and about 3.5 times as expensive as lead-acid batteries.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] may serve as future storage devices, since most vehicles are parked an average of 95 percent of the time, their batteries could be used to let electricity flow from the car to the power lines and back.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] ) to a very high speed of about 20,000 to over 50,000 rpm in a vacuum enclosure.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Flywheels can respond quickly as they store and feed back electricity into the grid in a matter of seconds.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] For reasons of reliability, distributed generation resources would be interconnected to the same transmission grid as central stations.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Various technical and economic issues occur in the integration of these resources into a grid.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Technical problems arise in the areas of power quality, voltage stability, harmonics, reliability, protection, and control.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Behavior of protective devices on the grid must be examined for all combinations of distributed and central station generation.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A large scale deployment of distributed generation may affect grid-wide functions such as frequency control and allocation of reserves.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] As a result, smart grid functions, virtual power plants and grid energy storage such as power to gas stations are added to the grid.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Conflicts occur between utilities and resource managing organizations.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Each distributed generation resource has its own integration issues.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Solar PV and wind power both have intermittent and unpredictable generation, so they create many stability issues for voltage and frequency.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] These voltage issues affect mechanical grid equipment, such as load tap changers, which respond too often and wear out much more quickly than utilities anticipated.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Also, without any form of energy storage during times of high solar generation, companies must rapidly increase generation around the time of sunset to compensate for the loss of solar generation.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This high ramp rate produces what the industry terms the *duck curve* that is a major concern for grid operators in the future.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Storage can fix these issues if it can be implemented.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Flywheels have shown to provide excellent frequency regulation.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Also, flywheels are highly cyclable compared to batteries, meaning they maintain the same energy and power after a significant amount of cycles( on the order of 10,000 cycles).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Short term use batteries, at a large enough scale of use, can help to flatten the duck curve and prevent generator use fluctuation and can help to maintain voltage profile.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] However, cost is a major limiting factor for energy storage as each technique is prohibitively expensive to produce at scale and comparatively not energy dense compared to liquid fossil fuels.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Finally, another method of aiding in integration is in the use of intelligent inverters that have the capability to also store the energy when there is more energy production than consumption.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] There have been some efforts to mitigate voltage and frequency issues due to increased implementation of DG.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Most notably, IEEE 1547 sets the standard for interconnection and interoperability of distributed energy resources.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] IEEE 1547 sets specific curves signaling when to clear a fault as a function of the time after the disturbance and the magnitude of the voltage irregularity or frequency irregularity.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Voltage issues also give legacy equipment the opportunity to perform new operations.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Notably, inverters can regulate the voltage output of DGs.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Changing inverter impedances can change voltage fluctuations of DG, meaning inverters have the ability to control DG voltage output.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] To reduce the effect of DG integration on mechanical grid equipment, transformers and load tap changers have the potential to implement specific tap operation vs. voltage operation curves mitigating the effect of voltage irregularities due to DG.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] That is, load tap changers respond to voltage fluctuations that last for a longer period than voltage fluctuations created from DG equipment.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] It is now possible to combine technologies such as photovoltaics, batteries and cogeneration to make stand alone distributed generation systems.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Recent work has shown that such systems have a low levelized cost of electricity.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Many authors now think that these technologies may enable a mass-scale grid defection because consumers can produce electricity using off grid systems primarily made up of solar photovoltaic technology.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] For example, the Rocky Mountain Institute has proposed that there may wide scale grid defection.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This is backed up by studies in the Midwest.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Cogenerators find favor because most buildings already burn fuels, and the cogeneration can extract more value from the fuel.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Local production has no electricity transmission losses on long distance power lines or energy losses from the Joule effect in transformers where in general 8-15% of the energy is lost (see also cost of electricity by source).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Some larger installations utilize combined cycle generation.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Usually this consists of a gas turbine whose exhaust boils water for a steam turbine in a Rankine cycle.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The condenser of the steam cycle provides the heat for space heating or an absorptive chiller.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Combined cycle plants with cogeneration have the highest known thermal efficiencies, often exceeding 85%.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In countries with high pressure gas distribution, small turbines can be used to bring the gas pressure to domestic levels whilst extracting useful energy.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] If the UK were to implement this countrywide an additional 2-4 GWe would become available.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A *microgrid* is a localized grouping of electricity generation, energy storage, and loads that normally operates connected to a traditional centralized grid (macrogrid).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This single point of common coupling with the macrogrid can be disconnected.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The microgrid can then function autonomously.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Generation and loads in a microgrid are usually interconnected at low voltage and it can operate in DC, AC, or the combination of both.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] From the point of view of the grid operator, a connected microgrid can be controlled as if it were one entity.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Microgrid generation resources can include stationary batteries, fuel cells, solar, wind, or other energy sources.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The multiple dispersed generation sources and ability to isolate the microgrid from a larger network would provide highly reliable electric power.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Produced heat from generation sources such as microturbines could be used for local process heating or space heating, allowing flexible trade off between the needs for heat and electric power.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Micro-grids have seen implementation in a number of communities over the world.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] For example, Tesla has implemented a solar micro-grid in the Samoan island of Ta'u, powering the entire island with solar energy.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This localized production system has helped save over 380 cubic metres (100,000 US gal) of diesel fuel.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] It is also able to sustain the island for three whole days if the sun were not to shine at all during that period.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] This is a great example of how micro-grid systems can be implemented in communities to encourage renewable resource usage and localized production.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] To plan and install Microgrids correctly, engineering modelling is needed.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Multiple simulation tools and optimization tools exist to model the economic and electric effects of Microgrids.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A widely used economic optimization tool is the Distributed Energy Resources Customer Adoption Model (DER-CAM) from Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] Another frequently used commercial economic modelling tool is Homer Energy, originally designed by the National Renewable Laboratory.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] There are also some power flow and electrical design tools guiding the Microgrid developers.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The Pacific Northwest National Laboratory designed the public available GridLAB-D tool and the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) designed OpenDSS to simulate the distribution system (for Microgrids).
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A professional integrated DER-CAM and OpenDSS version is available via BankableEnergy Archived 11 July 2018 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] A European tool that can be used for electrical, cooling, heating, and process heat demand simulation is EnergyPLAN from the Aalborg University, Denmark.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] In 2010 Colorado enacted a law requiring that by 2020 that 3% of the power generated in Colorado utilize distributed generation of some sort.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] On 11 October 2017, California Governor Jerry Brown signed into law a bill, SB 338, that makes utility companies plan "carbon-free alternatives to gas generation" in order to meet peak demand.
[src:smart-grid/distributed-generation] The law requires utilities to evaluate issues such as energy storage, efficiency, and distributed energy resources.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] An **electrical grid** (or **electricity network**) is an interconnected network for electricity delivery from producers to consumers.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electrical grids consist of power stations, electrical substations to step voltage up or down, electric power transmission to carry power over long distances, and finally electric power distribution to customers.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In that last step, voltage is stepped down again to the required service voltage.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Power stations are typically built close to energy sources and far from densely populated areas.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electrical grids vary in size and can cover whole countries or continents.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] From small to large there are microgrids, wide area synchronous grids, and super grids.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The combined transmission and distribution network is part of electricity delivery, known as the *power grid*.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Grids are nearly always synchronous, meaning all distribution areas operate with three phase alternating current (AC) frequencies synchronized (so that voltage swings occur at almost the same time).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This allows transmission of AC power throughout the area, connecting the electricity generators with consumers.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Grids can enable more efficient electricity markets.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Although electrical grids are widespread, as of 2016, 1.4 billion people worldwide were not connected to an electricity grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] As electrification increases, the number of people with access to grid electricity is growing.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] About 840 million people (mostly in Africa), which is ca.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] 11% of the World's population, had no access to grid electricity in 2017, down from 1.2 billion in 2010.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electrical grids can be prone to malicious intrusion or attack; thus, there is a need for electric grid security.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Also as electric grids modernize and introduce computer technology, cyber threats start to become a security risk.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Particular concerns relate to the more complex computer systems needed to manage grids.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A microgrid is a local grid that is usually part of the regional wide-area synchronous grid, but which can disconnect and operate autonomously.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] It might do this in times when the main grid is affected by outages.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This is known as islanding, and it might run indefinitely on its own resources.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Compared to larger grids, microgrids typically use a lower voltage distribution network and distributed generators.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Microgrids may not only be more resilient, but may be cheaper to implement in isolated areas.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A design goal is that a local area produces all of the energy it uses.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A *wide area synchronous grid* (also called an "interconnection" in North America) is an electrical grid at a regional scale or greater that operates at a synchronized frequency and is electrically tied together during normal system conditions.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For example, there are four major interconnections in North America (the Western Interconnection, the Eastern Interconnection, the Quebec Interconnection and the Texas Interconnection).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In Europe, one large grid connects most of Western Europe.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] These are also known as synchronous zones, the largest of which is the synchronous grid of Continental Europe (ENTSO-E) with 667 gigawatts (GW) of generation, and the widest region served being that of the IPS/UPS system serving countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Synchronous grids with ample capacity facilitate electricity market trading across wide areas.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the ENTSO-E in 2008, over 350,000 megawatt hours were sold per day on the European Energy Exchange (EEX).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Each of the interconnects in North America are run at a nominal 60 Hz, while those of Europe run at 50 Hz.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] One disadvantage of a wide-area synchronous grid is that problems in one part can have repercussions across the whole grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For example, in 2018, Kosovo used more power than it generated due to a dispute with Serbia, leading to the phase across the whole synchronous grid of Continental Europe lagging behind what it should have been.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This caused certain kinds of clocks to become six minutes slow.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A *super grid* or *supergrid* is a wide-area transmission network that is intended to make possible the trade of high volumes of electricity across great distances.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] It is sometimes also referred to as a *mega grid*.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Super grids can support a global energy transition by smoothing local fluctuations of wind energy and solar energy.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In this context, they are considered as a key technology to mitigate global warming.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Super grids typically use high-voltage direct current (HVDC) to transmit electricity long distances.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The latest generation of HVDC power lines can transmit energy with losses of only 1.6% per 1000 km.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electric utilities between regions are many times interconnected for improved economy and reliability.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electrical interconnectors allow for economies of scale, allowing energy to be purchased from large, efficient sources.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Utilities can draw power from generator reserves from a different region to ensure continuing, reliable power and diversify their loads.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Interconnection also allows regions to have access to cheap bulk energy by receiving power from different sources.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For example, one region may be producing cheap hydro power during high water seasons, but in low water seasons, another area may be producing cheaper power through wind, allowing both regions to access cheaper energy sources from one another during different times of the year.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Neighboring utilities also help others to maintain the overall system frequency and also help manage tie transfers between utility regions.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electricity Interconnection Level (EIL) of a grid is the ratio of the total interconnector power to the grid divided by the installed production capacity of the grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Within the EU, it has set a target of national grids reaching 10% by 2020, and 15% by 2030.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electricity generation is the process of generating electric power at power stations.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This is done ultimately from sources of primary energy typically with electromechanical generators driven by heat engines from fossil, nuclear, and geothermal sources, or driven by the kinetic energy of water or wind.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Other power sources are photovoltaics driven by solar insolation, and grid batteries.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The sum of the power outputs of generators on the grid is the production of the grid, typically measured in gigawatts (GW).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electric power transmission is the bulk movement of electrical energy from a generating site, via a web of interconnected lines, to an electrical substation, from which is connected to the distribution system.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This networked system of connections is distinct from the local wiring between high-voltage substations and customers.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Transmission networks are built with redundant pathways to prevent a single point of failure.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In case of line failures this redundancy allows power to be simply rerouted while repairs are done.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Because the power is often generated far from where it is consumed, the transmission system can cover great distances.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For a given amount of power, transmission efficiency is greater at higher voltages and lower currents.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Therefore, voltages are stepped up at the generating station, and stepped down at local substations for distribution to customers.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Three-phase, compared to single-phase, can deliver much more power for a given amount of wire, since the neutral and ground wires are shared.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Further, three-phase generators and motors are more efficient than their single-phase counterparts.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] However, for conventional conductors one of the main losses are resistive losses which are a square law on current, and depend on distance.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] High voltage AC transmission lines can lose 1–4% per hundred miles.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] However, high-voltage direct current can have half the losses of AC.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Over very long distances, these efficiencies can offset the additional cost of the required AC/DC converter stations at each end.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Substations may perform many different functions but usually transform voltage from low to high (step up) and from high to low (step down).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Between the generator and the final consumer, the voltage may be transformed several times.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Distribution is the final stage in the delivery of power; it carries electricity from the transmission system to individual consumers.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Substations connect to the transmission system and lower the transmission voltage to medium voltage ranging between 2 kV and 35 kV.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] But the voltage levels varies very much between different countries, in Sweden medium voltage are normally 10 kV between 20 kV.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Primary distribution lines carry this medium voltage power to distribution transformers located near the customer's premises.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Distribution transformers again lower the voltage to the utilization voltage.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Customers demanding a much larger amount of power may be connected directly to the primary distribution level or the subtransmission level.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Distribution networks are divided into two types, radial or network.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In cities and towns of North America, the grid tends to follow the classic *radially fed* design.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A substation receives its power from the transmission network, the power is stepped down with a transformer and sent to a bus from which feeders fan out in all directions across the countryside.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] These feeders carry three-phase power, and tend to follow the major streets near the substation.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] As the distance from the substation grows, the fanout continues as smaller laterals spread out to cover areas missed by the feeders.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This tree-like structure grows outward from the substation, but for reliability reasons, usually contains at least one unused backup connection to a nearby substation.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This connection can be enabled in case of an emergency, so that a portion of a substation's service territory can be alternatively fed by another substation.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] As of 2020, the largest form of grid energy storage is dammed hydroelectricity, with both conventional hydroelectric generation as well as pumped storage hydroelectricity.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Developments in battery storage have enabled commercially viable projects to store energy during peak production and release during peak demand, and for use when production unexpectedly falls giving time for slower responding resources to be brought online.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Two alternatives to grid storage are the use of peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps and demand response to shift load to other times.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The demand, or load on an electrical grid is the total electrical power being removed by the users of the grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The graph of the demand over time is called the *demand curve*.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Baseload is the minimum load on the grid over any given period, peak demand is the maximum load.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Historically, baseload was commonly met by equipment that was relatively cheap to run, that ran continuously for weeks or months at a time, but globally this is becoming less common.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The extra peak demand requirements are sometimes produced by expensive peaking plants that are generators optimised to come on-line quickly but these too are becoming less common.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] However, if the demand of electricity exceeds the capacity of a local power grid, it will cause safety issues like burning out.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Grids are designed to supply electricity to their customers at largely constant voltages.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This has to be achieved with varying demand, variable reactive loads, and even nonlinear loads, with electricity provided by generators and distribution and transmission equipment that are not perfectly reliable.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Often grids use tap changers on transformers near to the consumers to adjust the voltage and keep it within specification.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In a synchronous grid all the generators must run at the same frequency, and must stay very nearly in phase with each other and the grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Generation and consumption must be balanced across the entire grid, because energy is consumed as it is produced.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For rotating generators, a local governor regulates the driving torque, maintaining almost constant rotation speed as loading changes.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Energy is stored in the immediate short term by the rotational kinetic energy of the generators.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Although the speed is kept largely constant, small deviations from the nominal system frequency are very important in regulating individual generators and are used as a way of assessing the equilibrium of the grid as a whole.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] When the grid is lightly loaded the grid frequency runs above the nominal frequency, and this is taken as an indication by Automatic generation control (AGC) systems across the network that generators should reduce their output.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Conversely, when the grid is heavily loaded, the frequency naturally slows, and governors adjust their generators so that more power is output (droop speed control).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] When generators have identical droop speed control settings it ensures that multiple parallel generators with the same settings share load in proportion to their rating.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In addition, there's often central control, which can change the parameters of the AGC systems over timescales of a minute or longer to further adjust the regional network flows and the operating frequency of the grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For timekeeping purposes, the nominal frequency will be allowed to vary in the short term, but is adjusted to prevent line-operated clocks from gaining or losing significant time over the course of a whole 24 hour period.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Neighbouring grids that are not directly connected are almost always out-of-phase with each other.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Instead, high-voltage direct current lines or variable-frequency transformers are used, which allow two out-of-phase synchronous grids to share power.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The sum of the maximum power outputs (nameplate capacity) of the generators attached to an electrical grid might be considered to be the capacity of the grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] However, in practice, they are never run flat out simultaneously.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Typically, some generators are kept running at lower output powers (spinning reserve) to deal with failures as well as variation in demand.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In addition generators can be off-line for maintenance or other reasons, such as availability of energy inputs (fuel, water, wind, sun etc.) or pollution constraints.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Most grid codes specify that the load is shared between the generators in merit order according to their marginal cost (i.e. cheapest first) and sometimes their environmental impact.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Thus cheap electricity providers tend to be run flat out almost all the time, and the more expensive producers are only run when necessary.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A central authority is usually designated to facilitate communication and develop protocols to maintain a stable grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] For example, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation gained binding powers in the United States in 2006, and has advisory powers in the applicable parts of Canada and Mexico.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The U.S. government has also designated National Interest Electric Transmission Corridors, where it believes transmission bottlenecks have developed.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Where multiple utilities own generators connected to one electrical grid power pools are often formed which have agreements about responsibilities.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Each grid may have a system operator that is responsible for day-to-day running of one or more grids.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Failures are usually associated with generators or power transmission lines tripping circuit breakers due to faults leading to a loss of generation capacity for customers, or excess demand.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] This will often cause the frequency to reduce, and the remaining generators will react and together attempt to stabilize above the minimum.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] If that is not possible then a number of scenarios can occur.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A large failure in one part of the grid—unless quickly compensated for—can cause current to re-route itself to flow from the remaining generators to consumers over transmission lines of insufficient capacity, causing further failures.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] One downside to a widely connected grid is thus the possibility of cascading failure and widespread power outage.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A *brownout* is an intentional or unintentional drop in voltage in an electrical power supply system.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The reduction lasts for minutes or hours, as opposed to short-term voltage sag (or dip).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The term brownout comes from the dimming experienced by incandescent lighting when the voltage sags.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A voltage reduction may be an effect of disruption of an electrical grid, or may occasionally be imposed in an effort to reduce load and prevent a power outage, known as a blackout.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A *power outage* (also called a *power cut*, a *power out*, a *power blackout*, *power failure* or a *blackout*) is a loss of the electric power to a particular area.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Power failures can be caused by faults at power stations, damage to electric transmission lines, substations or other parts of the distribution system, a short circuit, cascading failure, fuse or circuit breaker operation, and human error.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Power failures are particularly critical at sites where the environment and public safety are at risk.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Institutions such as hospitals, sewage treatment plants, mines, shelters and the like will usually have backup power sources such as standby generators, which will automatically start up when electrical power is lost.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Other critical systems, such as telecommunication, are also required to have emergency power.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The battery room of a telephone exchange usually has arrays of lead–acid batteries for backup and also a socket for connecting a generator during extended periods of outage.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electrical generation and transmission systems may not always meet peak demand requirements— the greatest amount of electricity required by all utility customers within a given region.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In these situations, overall demand must be lowered, either by turning off service to some devices or cutting back the supply voltage (brownouts), in order to prevent uncontrolled service disruptions such as power outages (widespread blackouts) or equipment damage.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Utilities may impose load shedding on service areas via targeted blackouts, rolling blackouts or by agreements with specific high-use industrial consumers to turn off equipment at times of system-wide peak demand.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A *black start* is the process of restoring an electric power station or a part of an electric grid to operation without relying on the external electric power transmission network to recover from a total or partial shutdown.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Normally, the electric power used within the plant is provided from the station's own generators.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] If all of the plant's main generators are shut down, station service power is provided by drawing power from the grid through the plant's transmission line.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] However, during a wide-area outage, off-site power from the grid is not available.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the absence of grid power, a so-called black start needs to be performed to bootstrap the power grid into operation.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] To provide a black start, some power stations have small diesel generators, normally called the *black start diesel generator* (BSDG), which can be used to start larger generators (of several megawatts capacity), which in turn can be used to start the main power station generators.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Generating plants using steam turbines require station service power of up to 10% of their capacity for boiler feedwater pumps, boiler forced-draft combustion air blowers, and for fuel preparation.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] It is uneconomical to provide such a large standby capacity at each station, so black-start power must be provided over designated tie lines from another station.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Often hydroelectric power plants are designated as the black-start sources to restore network interconnections.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] A hydroelectric station needs very little initial power to start (just enough to open the intake gates and provide excitation current to the generator field coils), and can put a large block of power on line very quickly to allow start-up of fossil-fuel or nuclear stations.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Certain types of combustion turbine can be configured for black start, providing another option in places without suitable hydroelectric plants.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In 2017 a utility in Southern California has successfully demonstrated the use of a battery energy storage system to provide a black start, firing up a combined cycle gas turbine from an idle state.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Despite novel institutional arrangements and network designs, power delivery infrastructures is experiencing aging across the developed world.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Demand response is a grid management technique where retail or wholesale customers are requested or incentivised either electronically or manually to reduce their load.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Currently, transmission grid operators use demand response to request load reduction from major energy users such as industrial plants.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Technologies such as smart metering can encourage customers to use power when electricity is plentiful by allowing for variable pricing.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The smart grid is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Resistance to distributed generation among grid operators may encourage providers to leave the grid and instead distribute power to smaller geographies.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The Rocky Mountain Institute and other studies foresee widescale grid defection.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] However, grid defection may be less likely in places such as Germany that have greater power demands in the winter.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Early electric energy was produced near the device or service requiring that energy.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the 1880s, electricity competed with steam, hydraulics, and especially coal gas.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Coal gas was first produced on customer's premises but later evolved into gasification plants that enjoyed economies of scale.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the industrialized world, cities had networks of piped gas, used for lighting.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] But gas lamps produced poor light, wasted heat, made rooms hot and smoky, and gave off hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the 1880s electric lighting soon became advantageous compared to gas lighting.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Electric utility companies established central stations to take advantage of economies of scale and moved to centralized power generation, distribution, and system management.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] After the war of the currents was settled in favor of AC power, with long-distance power transmission it became possible to interconnect stations to balance the loads and improve load factors.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries have liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that have led to the separation of the electricity transmission business from the distribution business.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the United Kingdom, Charles Merz, of the Merz & McLellan consulting partnership, built the Neptune Bank Power Station near Newcastle upon Tyne in 1901, and by 1912 had developed into the largest integrated power system in Europe.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Merz was appointed head of a parliamentary committee and his findings led to the Williamson Report of 1918, which in turn created the Electricity (Supply) Act 1919.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The bill was the first step towards an integrated electricity system.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In 1925 the Weir Committee recommended the creation of a "national gridiron" and so the Electricity (Supply) Act 1926 created the Central Electricity Board (CEB).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The CEB standardized the nation's electricity supply and established the first synchronized AC grid, running at 132 kilovolts and 50 hertz but initially operated as regional grids.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] After brief overnight interconnection in 1937 they permanently and officially joined in 1938 becoming the UK National Grid.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In France, electrification began in the 1900s, with 700 communes in 1919, and 36,528 in 1938.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] At the same time, these close networks began to interconnect: Paris in 1907 at 12 kV, the Pyrénées in 1923 at 150 kV, and finally almost all of the country interconnected by 1938 at 220 kV.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In 1946, the grid was the world's most dense.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] That year the state nationalised the industry, by uniting the private companies as Électricité de France.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The frequency was standardised at 50 Hz, and the 225 kV network replaced 110 kV and 120 kV.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Since 1956, service voltage has been standardised at 220/380 V, replacing the previous 127/220 V.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] During the 1970s, the 400 kV network, the new European standard, was implemented.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Starting on May 29, 1986, the end user service voltage will progressively change to 230/400 V ±10%.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the United States in the 1920s, utilities formed joint-operations to share peak load coverage and backup power.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In 1934, with the passage of the Public Utility Holding Company Act (U.S.), electric utilities were recognized as public goods of importance and were given outlined restrictions and regulatory oversight of their operations.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 1992 required transmission line owners to allow electric generation companies open access to their network and led to a restructuring of how the electric industry operated in an effort to create competition in power generation.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] No longer were electric utilities built as vertical monopolies, where generation, transmission and distribution were handled by a single company.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] Now, the three stages could be split among various companies, in an effort to provide fair access to high voltage transmission.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 allowed incentives and loan guarantees for alternative energy production and advance innovative technologies that avoided greenhouse emissions.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In China, electrification began in the 1950s.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In August 1961, the electrification of the Baoji-Fengzhou section of the Baocheng Railway was completed and delivered for operation, becoming China's first electrified railway.
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] From 1958 to 1998, China's electrified railway reached 6,200 miles (10,000 kilometres).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] As of the end of 2017, this number has reached 54,000 miles (87,000 kilometres).
[src:smart-grid/electrical-grid] In the current railway electrification system of China, State Grid Corporation of China—Archived 2021-12-21 at the Wayback Machine—is an important power supplier.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, the largest form of grid storage is pumped-storage hydroelectricity, with utility-scale batteries and behind-the-meter batteries coming second and third.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are well suited for short-duration storage (under 8 hours), due to their lower cost and sensitivity to degradation at high states of charge.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries and compressed air energy storage may provide storage for medium-duration.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Two forms of storage are suited for long-duration storage: green hydrogen, produced via electrolysis and thermal energy storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage is one option to making grids more flexible.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Another solution is the use of more dispatchable power plants that can change their output rapidly, for instance peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Demand response can shift load to other times and interconnections between regions can balance out fluctuations in renewables production.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The price of storage technologies typically goes down with experience.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, lithium-ion batteries have been getting some 20% cheaper for each doubling of worldwide capacity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Systems with under 40% variable renewables need only short-term storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] At 80%, medium-duration storage becomes essential and beyond 90%, long-duration storage does too.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging, and alternative flexibility options like demand response may be more economic.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Any electrical power grid must match electricity production to consumption, both of which vary significantly over time.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy derived from solar and wind sources varies with the weather on time scales ranging from less than a second to weeks or longer.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Nuclear power is less flexible than fossil fuels, meaning it cannot easily match the variations in demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Thus, low-carbon electricity without storage presents special challenges to electric utilities.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is one of the three key ways to replace flexibility from fossil fuels in the grid.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Other options are demand-side response, in which consumers change when they use electricity or how much they use.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, households may have cheaper night tariffs to encourage them to use electricity at night.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Industry and commercial consumers can also change their demand to meet supply.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Improved network interconnection smooths the variations of renewables production and demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] When there is little wind in one location, another might have a surplus of production.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Expansion of transmission lines usually takes a long time.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage has a large set of roles in the electricity grid and can therefore provide many different services.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, it can arbitrage by keeping it until the electricity price rises, it can help make the grid more stable, and help reduce investment into transmission infrastructure.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The type of service provided by storage depends on who manages the technology, whether the technology is based alongside generation of electricity, within the network, or at the side of consumption.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Providing short-term flexibility is a key role for energy storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, it can help with the integration of variable renewable energy, storing it when there is an oversupply of wind and solar and electricity prices are low.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] More generally, it can exploit the changes in prices of electricity over time in the wholesale market, charging when electricity is cheap and selling when it is expensive.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can further help with grid congestion (where there is insufficient capacity on transmission lines).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Consumers can use storage to use more of their self-produced electricity (for instance from rooftop solar power).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage can also be used to provide essential grid services.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, storage can smooth out the variations in production, for instance for solar and wind.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can assist in a black start after a power outage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the network side, these include frequency regulation (continuously) and frequency response (after unexpected changes in supply or demand).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the consumption side, storage can improve the quality of the delivered electricity in less stable grids.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Investment in storage may make some investments in the transmission and distribution network unnecessary, or may allow them to be scaled down.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Additionally, storage can ensure there is sufficient capacity to meet peak demand within the electricity grid.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Finally, in off-grid home systems or mini-grids, electricity storage can help provide energy access in areas that were previously not connected to the electricity grid.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Recent advances in artificial intelligence and machine learning allow for real-time optimization of energy storage assets.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Reinforcement learning algorithms are being explored to maximize arbitrage, manage degradation, and respond to market signals, particularly in complex and high-renewable systems.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy from sunlight or other renewable energy is converted to potential energy for storage in devices such as electric batteries.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The stored potential energy is later converted to electricity that is added to the power grid, even when the original energy source is not available.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In daytime, different renewable sources provide different amounts of power to the grid.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] At night, energy is provided by batteries that were charged during the day when renewable energy exceeded customer demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be stored directly for a short time in capacitors, somewhat longer electrochemically in batteries, and much longer chemically (e.g. hydrogen), mechanically (e.g. pumped hydropower) or as heat.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The first pumped hydroelectricity was constructed at the end of the 19th century around the Alps in Italy, Austria, and Switzerland.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The technique rapidly expanded during the 1960s to 1980s nuclear boom, due to nuclear power's inability to quickly adapt to changes in electricity demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the 21st century, interest in storage surged due to the rise of sustainable energy sources, which are often weather-dependent.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Commercial batteries have been available for over a century.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, their widespread use in the power grid is more recent, with only 1 GW available in 2013.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are the most commonly used batteries for grid applications, as of 2024, following the application of batteries in electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In comparison with EVs, grid batteries require less energy density, meaning that more emphasis can be put on costs, the ability to charge and discharge often and lifespan.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This has led to a shift towards lithium iron phosphate batteries (LFP batteries), which are cheaper and last longer than traditional lithium-ion batteries.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Costs of batteries are declining rapidly; from 2010 to 2023 costs fell by 90%.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, utility-scale systems account for two thirds of added capacity, and home applications (behind-the-meter) for one third.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are highly suited to short-duration storage (<8h) due to cost and degradation associated with high states of charge.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The electric vehicle fleet has a large overall battery capacity, which can potentially be used for grid energy storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This could be in the form of vehicle-to-grid (V2G), where cars store energy when they are not in use, or by repurposing batteries from cars at the end of the vehicle's life.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Car batteries typically range between 33 and 100 kWh; for comparison, a typical upper-middle-class household in Spain might use some 18 kWh in a day.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] By 2030, batteries in electric vehicles may be able to meet all short-term storage demand globally.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been more than 100 V2G pilot projects globally.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The effect of V2G charging on battery life can be positive or negative.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Increased cycling of batteries can lead to faster degradation, but due to better management of the state of charge and gentler charging and discharging, V2G might instead increase the lifetime of batteries.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Second-hand batteries may be useable for stationary grid storage for roughly 6 years, when their capacity drops from roughly 80% to 60% of the initial capacity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] LFP batteries are particularly suitable for reusing, as they degrade less than other lithium-ion batteries and recycling is less attractive as their materials are not as valuable.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In redox flow batteries, energy is stored in liquids, which are placed in two separate tanks.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] When charging or discharging, the liquids are pumped into a cell with the electrodes.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The amount of energy stored (as set by the size of the tanks) can be adjusted separately from the power output (as set by the speed of the pumps).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries have the advantages of low capital cost for charge-discharge duration over 4 h, and of long durability (many years).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries are inferior to lithium-ion batteries in terms of energy efficiency, averaging efficiencies between 60% and 75%.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium redox batteries is most commercially advanced type of flow battery, with roughly 40 companies making them as of 2022.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Sodium-ion batteries are a possible alternative to lithium-ion batteries, as they are less flammable, and use cheaper and less critical materials.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] They have a lower energy density, and possibly a shorter lifespan.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] If produced at the same scale as lithium-ion batteries, they may become 20% to 30% cheaper.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Iron-air batteries may be suitable for even longer duration storage than flow batteries (weeks), but the technology is not yet mature.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage in supercapacitors works well for applications where a lot of power is needed for short amount of time.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the power grid, they are therefore mostly used in short-term frequency regulation.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Various power-to-gas and power-to-fuel technologies exist that can convert excess electricity into an easier to store chemical.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The lowest cost and most efficient one is hydrogen.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, it is easier to use synthetic methane with existing infrastructure and appliances, as it is very similar to natural gas.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been a number of demonstration plants where hydrogen is burned in gas turbines, either co-firing with natural gas, or on its own.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Similarly, a number of coal plants have demonstrated it is possible to co-fire ammonia when burning coal.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In 2022, there was also a small pilot to burn pure ammonia in a gas turbine.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] A portion of existing gas turbines are capable of co-firing hydrogen, which means there is, as a lower estimate, 80 GW of capacity ready to burn hydrogen.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be used as a long-term storage medium.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Green hydrogen is produced from the electrolysis of water and converted back into electricity in an internal combustion engine, or a fuel cell, with a round-trip efficiency of roughly 41%.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Together with thermal storage, it is expected to be best suited to seasonal energy storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be stored aboveground in tanks or underground in larger quantities.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Underground storage is easiest in salt caverns, but only a certain number of places have suitable geology.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage in porous rocks, for instance in empty gas fields and some aquifers, can store hydrogen at a larger scale, but this type of storage may have some drawbacks.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, some of the hydrogen can leak or react to form hydrogen sulfide (H₂S) or methane.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be converted into ammonia in a reaction with nitrogen in the Haber-Bosch process.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia, a gas at room temperature, is more expensive to produce than hydrogen.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, it can be stored more cheaply than hydrogen.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Tank storage is usually done at between one and ten times atmospheric pressure and at a temperature of −30 °C (−22 °F), in liquid form.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia has multiple uses besides being an energy carrier: it is the basis for the production of many chemicals; the most common use is for fertilizer.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can be used for power generation directly, or converted back to hydrogen first.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternatively, it has potential applications as a fuel in shipping.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It is possible to further convert hydrogen into methane via the Sabatier reaction, a chemical reaction which combines CO2 and H2.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] While the reaction that converts CO from gasified coal into CH4 is mature, the process to form methane out of CO2 is less so.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Efficiencies of around 80% one-way can be achieved, that is, some 20% of the energy in hydrogen is lost in the reaction.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flywheels store energy in the form of mechanical energy.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] They are suited to supplying high levels of electricity over minutes and can also be charged rapidly.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] They have a long lifetime and can be used in settings with widely varying temperatures.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The technology is mature, but more expensive than batteries and supercapacitors and not used frequently.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, pumped-storage hydroelectricity (PSH) was the largest form of grid energy storage globally, with an installed capacity of 181 GW, surpassing the combined capacity of utility-scale and behind-the-meter battery storage, which totaled approximately 88 GW.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] PSH is particularly effective for managing daily fluctuations in energy demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] During periods of low demand, water is pumped to a higher-elevation reservoir, and during peak demand, the stored water is released to generate electricity through turbines.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The system has an efficiency rate of 75% to 85% and can quickly respond to changes in demand, typically within seconds to minutes.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] While traditional PSH systems require specific geographical conditions, alternative designs have been proposed.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] These include using deep salt caverns or constructing hollow structures on the seabed, where the ocean serves as the upper reservoir.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, PSH construction is often expensive, time-consuming, and can have significant environmental and social impacts on nearby communities.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Installing floating solar panels on reservoirs, can increase the efficiency of PSH systems.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] These panels reduce water evaporation and benefit from cooling by the water surface, which also improves their energy generation efficiency.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams with large reservoirs can also be operated to provide peak generation at times of peak demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Water is stored in the reservoir during periods of low demand and released through the plant when demand is higher.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] While technically no electricity is stored, the net effect is similar to that of pumped storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams typically offer more storage capacity than dedicated pumped-storage systems.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Upgrades may be needed so that these dams can respond to variable demand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, additional investment may be needed in transmission lines, or additional turbines may need to be installed to increase the peak output from the dam.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As well as energy generation, they often play a role in flood defense and protection of ecosystems, recreation, and they supply water for irrigation.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This means it is not always possible to change their operation much, but even with low flexibility, they may still play an important role in responding to changes in wind and solar production.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternative methods that use gravity include storing energy by moving large solid masses upward against gravity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This can be achieved inside old mine shafts or in specially constructed towers where heavy weights are winched up to store energy and allowed a controlled descent to release it.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Compressed air energy storage (CAES) stores electricity by compressing air.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The compressed air is typically stored in large underground caverns.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The expanding air can be used to drive turbines, converting the energy back into electricity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As air cools when expanding, some heat needs to be added in this stage to prevent freezing.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This can be provided by a low-carbon source, or in the case of advanced CAES, by reusing the heat that is released when air is compressed.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, there are three advanced CAES projects in operation in China.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Typical efficiencies of advanced CAES are between 60% and 80%.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Another electricity storage method is to compress and cool air, turning it into liquid air, which can be stored and expanded when needed, turning a turbine to generate electricity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This is called liquid air energy storage (LAES).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The air would be cooled to temperatures of −196 °C (−320.8 °F) to become liquid.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Like with compressed air, heat is needed for the expansion step.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the case of LAES, low-grade industrial heat can be used for this.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy efficiency for LAES lies between 50% and 70%.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, LAES is moving from pre-commercial to commercial.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] An alternative is the compression of CO 2 to store electricity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be directly stored thermally with a Carnot battery.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] A Carnot battery is a type of energy storage system that stores electricity in heat storage and converts the stored heat back to electricity via thermodynamic cycles (for instance, a turbine).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] While less efficient than pumped hydro or battery storage, this type of system is expected to be cheap and can provide long-duration storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] A pumped-heat electricity storage system is a Carnot battery that uses a reversible heat pump to convert the electricity into heat.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It usually stores the energy in both a hot and cold reservoir.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] To achieve decent efficiencies (>50%), the temperature ratio between the two must reach a factor of 5.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Thermal energy storage is also used in combination with concentrated solar power (CSP).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In CSP, solar energy is first converted into heat, and then either directly converted into electricity or first stored.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The energy is released when there is little or no sunshine.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This means that CSP can be used as a dispatchable (flexible) form of generation.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The energy in a CSP system can for instance be stored in molten salts or in a solid medium such as sand.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Finally, heating and cooling systems in buildings can be controlled to store thermal energy in either the building's mass or dedicated thermal storage tanks.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This thermal storage can provide load-shifting or even more complex ancillary services by increasing power consumption (charging the storage) during off-peak times and lowering power consumption (discharging the storage) during higher-priced peak times.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The levelized cost of storing electricity (LCOS) is a measure of the lifetime costs of storing electricity per MWh of electricity discharged.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It includes investment costs, but also operational costs and charging costs.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] It depends highly on storage type and purpose; as subsecond-scale frequency regulation, minute/hour-scale peaker plants, or day/week-scale season storage.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For power applications (for instance around ancillary services or black starts), a similar metric is the annuitized capacity cost (ACC), which measures the lifetime costs per kW.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] ACC is lowest when there are few cycles (<300) and when the discharge is less than one hour.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This is because the technology is reimbursed only when it provides spare capacity, not when it is discharged.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The cost of storage is coming down following technology-dependent experience curves, the price drop for each doubling in cumulative capacity (or experience).
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion battery prices fall rapidly: the price utilities pay for them falls 19% with each doubling of capacity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen production via electrolysis has a similar learning rate, but it is much more uncertain.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium-flow batteries typically get 14% cheaper for each doubling of capacity.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Pumped hydropower has not seen prices fall much with increased experience.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Before 2020, most value for storage was in providing power quality services.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Arbitrage is the service with the largest economic potential for storage applications.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] In systems with under 40% of variable renewables, only short-term storage (of less than 4 hours) is needed for integration.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] When the share of variable renewables climbs to 80%, medium-duration storage (between 4 and 16 hours, for instance compressed air) is needed.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Above 90%, large-scale long-duration storage is required.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging even then, as the costs are high.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternative flexibility options, such as demand response, network expansions or flexible generation (geothermal or fossil gas with carbon capture and storage) may be lower-cost.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Like with renewables, storage will "cannibalise" its own income, but even more strongly.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] That is, with more storage on the market, there is less of an opportunity to do arbitrage or deliver other services to the grid.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] How markets are designed impacts revenue potential too.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] The income from arbitrage is quite variable between years, whereas markets that have capacity payments likely show less volatility.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is not 100% efficient, so more electricity needs to be bought than can be sold.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] This implies that if there is only a small variation in price, it may not be economical to charge and discharge.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, if the storage application is 75% efficient, the price at which the electricity is sold needs to be at least 1.33 higher than the price for which it was bought.
[src:smart-grid/grid-energy-storage] Typically, electricity prices vary most between day and night, which means that storage up to 8 hours has relatively high potential for profit.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The **smart grid** is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The first alternating current power grid system was installed in 1886 in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] At that time, the grid was a centralized unidirectional system of electric power transmission, electricity distribution, and demand-driven control.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the 20th century, local grids grew over time and were eventually interconnected for economic and reliability reasons.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Power stations were located strategically to be close to fossil fuel reserves (either the mines or wells themselves or else close to rail, road, or port supply lines).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Siting of hydroelectric dams in mountain areas also strongly influenced the structure of the emerging grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Nuclear power plants were sited for the availability of cooling water.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Finally, fossil fuel-fired power stations were initially very polluting and were sited as far as economically possible from population centres once electricity distribution networks permitted it.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] By the late 1960s, the electricity grid reached the overwhelming majority of the population of developed countries, with only outlying regional areas remaining 'off-grid'.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Metering of electricity consumption was necessary on a per-user basis in order to allow appropriate billing according to the (highly variable) level of consumption of different users.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Because of limited data collection and processing capability during the period of growth of the grid, fixed-tariff arrangements were commonly put in place, as well as dual-tariff arrangements where night-time power was charged at a lower rate than daytime power.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The motivation for dual-tariff arrangements was the lower night-time demand.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The metering capabilities of the 1960s grid meant technological limitations on the degree to which price signals could be propagated through the system.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] From the 1970s to the 1990s, growing demand led to increasing numbers of power stations.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In some areas, the supply of electricity, especially at peak times, could not keep up with this demand, resulting in poor power quality including blackouts, power cuts, and brownouts.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Increasingly, electricity was depended on for industry, heating, communication, lighting, and entertainment, and consumers demanded ever-higher levels of reliability.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Towards the end of the 20th century, electricity demand patterns were established: domestic heating and air-conditioning led to daily peaks in demand that were met by an array of 'peaking power generators' that would only be turned on for short periods each day.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the 21st century, some developing countries like China, India, and Brazil were seen as pioneers of smart grid deployment.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Since the early 21st century, opportunities to take advantage of improvements in electronic communication technology to resolve the limitations and costs of the electrical grid have become apparent.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Technological limitations on metering no longer force peak power prices to be averaged out and passed on to all consumers equally.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In parallel, growing concerns over environmental damage from fossil-fired power stations have led to a desire to use large amounts of renewable energy.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Dominant forms such as wind power and solar power are highly variable, and so the need for more sophisticated control systems became apparent, to facilitate the connection of sources to the otherwise highly controllable grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Power from photovoltaic cells (and to lesser extent wind turbines) has also, significantly, called into question the imperative for large, centralised power stations.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The rapidly falling costs point to a major change from the centralised grid topology to one that is highly distributed, with power being both generated *and* consumed right at the limits of the grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Finally, growing concern over terrorist attacks in some countries has led to calls for a more robust energy grid that is less dependent on centralised power stations that were perceived to be potential attack targets.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The first official definition of Smart Grid was provided by the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA-2007), which was approved by the US Congress in January 2007, and signed to law by President George W.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] That definition was used in the European Commission Communication (2011) 202.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A common element to most definitions is the application of digital processing and communications to the power grid, making data flow and information management central to the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Various capabilities result from the deeply integrated use of digital technology with power grids.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Integration of the new grid information is one of the key issues in the design of smart grids.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Much of the work that has been going on in electric grid modernization, especially substation and distribution automation, is now included in the general concept of the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid technologies emerged from earlier attempts at using electronic control, metering, and monitoring.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the 1980s, automatic meter reading was used for monitoring loads from large customers and evolved into the Advanced Metering Infrastructure of the 1990s, whose meters could store how electricity was used at different times of the day.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart meters add continuous communications so that monitoring can be done in real-time, and can be used as a gateway to demand response-aware devices and "smart sockets" in the home.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Early forms of such demand side management technologies were dynamic demand aware devices that passively sensed the load on the grid by monitoring changes in the power supply frequency.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Devices such as industrial and domestic air conditioners, refrigerators, and heaters adjusted their duty cycle to avoid activation during times the grid was suffering a peak condition.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Beginning in 2000, Italy's Telegestore Project was the first to network large numbers (27 million) of homes using smart meters connected via low bandwidth power line communication.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Some experiments used the term broadband over power lines (BPL), while others used wireless technologies such as mesh networking promoted for more reliable connections to disparate devices in the home as well as supporting metering of other utilities such as gas and water.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Monitoring and synchronization of wide-area networks were revolutionized in the early 1990s when the Bonneville Power Administration expanded its smart grid research with prototype sensors that are capable of very rapid analysis of anomalies in electricity quality over very large geographic areas.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The culmination of this work was the first operational Wide Area Measurement System (WAMS) in 2000.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Other countries are rapidly integrating this technology — China started having a comprehensive national WAMS when the past 5-year economic plan was completed in 2012.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The earliest deployments of smart grids include the Italian system *Telegestore* (2005), the mesh network of Austin, Texas (since 2003), and the smart grid in Boulder, Colorado (2008).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] See § Deployments and attempted deployments below.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid would allow the power industry to observe and control parts of the system at higher resolution in time and space.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] One of the purposes of the smart grid is real time information exchange to make operation as efficient as possible.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] It would allow management of the grid on all time scales from high-frequency switching devices on a microsecond scale, to wind and solar output variations on a minute scale, to the future effects of the carbon emissions generated by power production on a decade scale.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Because of the diverse range of factors, there are numerous competing taxonomies and no agreement on a universal definition.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Nevertheless, one possible categorization is given here.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid makes use of technologies such as state estimation, that improve fault detection and allow self-healing of the network without the intervention of technicians.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] This will ensure a more reliable supply of electricity and reduce vulnerability to natural disasters or attacks.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Although multiple routes are touted as a feature of the smart grid, the old grid also featured multiple routes.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Initial power lines in the grid were built using a radial model, later connectivity was guaranteed via multiple routes, referred to as a network structure.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] However, this created a new problem: if the current flow or related effects across the network exceed the limits of any particular network element, it could fail, and the current would be shunted to other network elements, which eventually may fail also, causing a domino effect.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A technique to prevent this is load shedding by rolling blackout or voltage reduction (brownout).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Classic grids were designed for a one-way flow of electricity, but if a local sub-network generates more power than it is consuming, the reverse flow can raise safety and reliability issues.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid aims to manage these situations.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The overall effect is less redundancy in transmission and distribution lines, and greater utilization of generators, leading to lower power prices.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The total load connected to the power grid can vary significantly over time.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Although the total load is the sum of many individual choices of the clients, the overall load is not necessarily stable or slow varying.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] For example, if a popular television program starts, millions of televisions will start to draw current instantly.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Traditionally, to respond to a rapid increase in power consumption, faster than the start-up time of a large generator, some spare generators are put on a dissipative standby mode.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid may warn all individual television sets, or another larger customer, to reduce the load temporarily (to allow time to start up a larger generator) or continuously (in the case of limited resources).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Using mathematical prediction algorithms it is possible to predict how many standby generators need to be used, to reach a certain failure rate.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the traditional grid, the failure rate can only be reduced at the cost of more standby generators.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In a smart grid, the load reduction by even a small portion of the clients may eliminate the problem.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] To reduce demand during the high-cost peak usage periods, communications and metering technologies inform smart devices in the home and business when energy demand is high and track how much electricity is used and when it is used.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] It also gives utility companies the ability to reduce consumption by communicating to devices directly in order to prevent system overloads.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Examples would be a utility reducing the usage of a group of electric vehicle charging stations or shifting temperature set points of air conditioners in a city.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] To motivate them to cut back use and perform what is called **peak curtailment** or **peak leveling**, prices of electricity are increased during high demand periods and decreased during low demand periods.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] It is thought that consumers and businesses will tend to consume less during high-demand periods if it is possible for consumers and consumer devices to be aware of the high price premium for using electricity at peak periods.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] This could mean making trade-offs such as cycling on/off air conditioners or running dishwashers at 9 pm instead of 5 pm.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] When businesses and consumers see a direct economic benefit of using energy at off-peak times, the theory is that they will include the energy cost of operation into their consumer device and building construction decisions and hence become more energy efficient.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Current network infrastructure is not built to allow for many distributed feed-in points, and typically even if some feed-in is allowed at the local (distribution) level, the transmission-level infrastructure cannot accommodate it.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Rapid fluctuations in distributed generation, such as due to cloudy or gusty weather, present significant challenges to power engineers who need to ensure stable power levels through varying the output of the more controllable generators such as gas turbines and hydroelectric generators.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid technology is a necessary condition for very large amounts of renewable electricity on the grid for this reason.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] There is also support for vehicle-to-grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid allows for systematic communication between suppliers (their energy price) and consumers (their willingness-to-pay), and permits both the suppliers and the consumers to be more flexible and sophisticated in their operational strategies.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Only the critical loads will need to pay the peak energy prices, and consumers will be able to be more strategic in when they use energy.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Generators with greater flexibility will be able to sell energy strategically for maximum profit, whereas inflexible generators such as base-load steam turbines and wind turbines will receive a varying tariff based on the level of demand and the status of the other generators currently operating.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The overall effect is a signal that awards energy efficiency, and energy consumption that is sensitive to the time-varying limitations of the supply.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] At the domestic level, appliances with a degree of energy storage or thermal mass (such as refrigerators, heat banks, and heat pumps) will be well placed to 'play' the market and seek to minimise energy cost by adapting demand to the lower-cost energy support periods.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] This is an extension of the dual-tariff energy pricing mentioned above.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Demand response support allows generators and loads to interact in an automated fashion in real-time, coordinating demand to flatten spikes.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Eliminating the fraction of demand that occurs in these spikes eliminates the cost of adding reserve generators, cuts wear and tear and extends the life of equipment, and allows users to cut their energy bills by telling low priority devices to use energy only when it is cheapest.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Currently, power grid systems have varying degrees of communication within control systems for their high-value assets, such as in generating plants, transmission lines, substations, and major energy users.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In general, information flows one way, from the users and the loads they control back to the utilities.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The utilities attempt to meet the demand and succeed or fail to varying degrees (brownouts, rolling blackout, uncontrolled blackout).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The total amount of power demanded by the users can have a very wide probability distribution which requires spare generating plants in standby mode to respond to the rapidly changing power usage.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] This one-way flow of information is expensive; the last 10% of generating capacity may be required as little as 1% of the time, and brownouts and outages can be costly to consumers.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Demand response can be provided by commercial, residential loads, and industrial loads.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified Demand Response Resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term mega-battery.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Latency of the data flow is a major concern, with some early smart meter architectures allowing actually as long as 24 hours delay in receiving the data, preventing any possible reaction by either supplying or demanding devices.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The bulk of smart grid technologies are already used in other applications such as manufacturing and telecommunications and are being adapted for use in grid operations.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Many different concepts have been used to model intelligent power grids.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] They are generally studied within the framework of complex systems.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In a recent brainstorming session, the power grid was considered within the context of optimal control, ecology, human cognition, glassy dynamics, information theory, microphysics of clouds, and many others.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Here is a selection of the types of analyses that have appeared in recent years.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Evans in their study introduced the concept of a substation based smart protection and hybrid Inspection Unit.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The power grid has been mapped onto variations of the Kuramoto model, a well-studied framework for synchronization of nonlinear oscillators.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The model describes how the electrical system keeps the power balance, to maintain phase synchronization (also known as phase locking).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Strictly speaking, the model is most used for an ordinary electrical grid, to determine, for instance, the role of branch insertions or of parameters dispersion.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Non-uniform oscillators also help to model different technologies, different types of power generators, patterns of consumption, and so on.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The model has also been used to describe the synchronization patterns in the blinking of fireflies.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Network Simulators are used to simulate/emulate network communication effects.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] This typically involves setting up a lab with the smart grid devices, applications etc. with the virtual network being provided by the network simulator.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Neural networks have been considered for power grid management as well.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Electric power systems can be classified in multiple different ways: non-linear, dynamic, discrete, or random.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) attempt to solve the most difficult of these problems, the non-linear problems.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] One application of ANNs is in demand forecasting.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In order for grids to operate economically and reliably, demand forecasting is essential, because it is used to predict the amount of power that will be consumed by the load.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] This is dependent on weather conditions, type of day, random events, incidents, etc.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] For non-linear loads though, the load profile isn't smooth and as predictable, resulting in higher uncertainty and less accuracy using the traditional Artificial Intelligence models.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] An example of the last case would be given the type of day, whether its weekday or weekend, that wouldn't have much of an effect on Hospital grids, but it'd be a big factor in resident housing grids' load profile.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] As wind power continues to gain popularity, it becomes a necessary ingredient in realistic power grid studies.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Off-line storage, wind variability, supply, demand, pricing, and other factors can be modelled as a mathematical game.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Here the goal is to develop a winning strategy.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Markov processes have been used to model and study this type of system.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] In 2009, the US smart grid industry was valued at about $21.4 billion – by 2014, it will exceed at least $42.8 billion.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Given the success of the smart grids in the U.S., the world market is expected to grow at a faster rate, surging from $69.3 billion in 2009 to $171.4 billion by 2014.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] With the segments set to benefit the most will be smart metering hardware sellers and makers of software used to transmit and organize the massive amount of data collected by meters.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A 2011 study from the Electric Power Research Institute concludes that investment in a U.S. smart grid will cost up to $476 billion over 20 years but will provide up to $2 trillion in customer benefits over that time.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A 2019 study from International Energy Agency estimates that the current (depreciated) value of the US electric grid is more than US$1 trillion.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The total cost of replacing it with a smart grid is estimated to be more than US$4 trillion.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] If smart grids are deployed fully across the US, the country expects to save US$130 billion annually.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] As customers can choose their electricity suppliers, depending on their different tariff methods, the focus of transportation costs will be increased.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Reduction of maintenance and replacements costs will stimulate more advanced control.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A 2003 United States Department of Energy study calculated that internal modernization of US grids with smart grid capabilities would save between 46 and 117 billion dollars over the next 20 years if implemented within a few years of the study.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] As well as these industrial modernization benefits, smart grid features could expand energy efficiency beyond the grid into the home by coordinating low priority home devices such as water heaters so that their use of power takes advantage of the most desirable energy sources.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids can also coordinate the production of power from large numbers of small power producers such as owners of rooftop solar panels — an arrangement that would otherwise prove problematic for power systems operators at local utilities.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] One important question is whether consumers will act in response to market signals.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Another concern is that the cost of telecommunications to fully support smart grids may be prohibitive.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] A less expensive communication mechanism is proposed using a form of "dynamic demand management" where devices shave peaks by shifting their loads in reaction to grid frequency.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Grid frequency could be used to communicate load information without the need of an additional telecommunication network, but it would not support economic bargaining or quantification of contributions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] Although there are specific and proven smart grid technologies in use, *smart grid* is an aggregate term for a set of related technologies on which a specification is generally agreed, rather than a name for a specific technology.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p01] The increased efficiency and reliability of the smart grid is expected to save consumers money and help reduce CO2 emissions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Most opposition and concerns have centered on smart meters and the items (such as remote control, remote disconnect, and variable rate pricing) enabled by them.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Where opposition to smart meters is encountered, they are often marketed as "smart grid" which connects smart grid to smart meters in the eyes of opponents.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] While modernization of electrical grids into smart grids allows for optimization of everyday processes, a smart grid, being online, can be vulnerable to cyberattacks.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Transformers which increase the voltage of electricity created at power plants for long-distance travel, transmission lines themselves, and distribution lines which deliver the electricity to its consumers are particularly susceptible.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] These systems rely on sensors which gather information from the field and then deliver it to control centers, where algorithms automate analysis and decision-making processes.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] These decisions are sent back to the field, where existing equipment execute them.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Hackers have the potential to disrupt these automated control systems, severing the channels which allow generated electricity to be utilized.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This is called a denial of service or DoS attack.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] They can also launch integrity attacks which corrupt information being transmitted along the system as well as desynchronization attacks which affect when such information is delivered to the appropriate location.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, intruders can gain access via renewable energy generation systems and smart meters connected to the grid, taking advantage of more specialized weaknesses or ones whose security has not been prioritized.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Because a smart grid has a large number of access points, like smart meters, defending all of its weak points can prove difficult.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) have evolved to target smart grids by reprogramming Programmable Logic Controllers (PLCs) to display false 'normal' operating conditions to operators while causing physical damage.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] To counter these vulnerabilities, experts recommend shifting from traditional network segmentation to 'micro-segmentation' and adopting 'zero-trust' models that require verification at every layer of the infrastructure.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] There is also concern on the security of the infrastructure, primarily that involving communications technology.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Concerns chiefly center around the communications technology at the heart of the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Designed to allow real-time contact between utilities and meters in customers' homes and businesses, there is a risk that these capabilities could be exploited for criminal or even terrorist actions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the key capabilities of this connectivity is the ability to remotely switch off power supplies, enabling utilities to quickly and easily cease or modify supplies to customers who default on payment.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This is undoubtedly a massive boon for energy providers, but also raises some significant security issues.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Cybercriminals have infiltrated the U.S. electric grid before on numerous occasions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Aside from computer infiltration, there are also concerns that computer malware like Stuxnet, which targeted SCADA systems which are widely used in industry, could be used to attack a smart grid network.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Electricity theft is a concern in the U.S. where the smart meters being deployed use RF technology to communicate with the electricity transmission network.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] People with knowledge of electronics can devise interference devices to cause the smart meter to report lower than actual usage.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Similarly, the same technology can be employed to make it appear that the energy the consumer is using is being used by another customer, increasing their bill.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The damage from a well-executed, sizable cyberattack could be extensive and long-lasting.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] One incapacitated substation could take from nine days to over a year to repair, depending on the nature of the attack.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It can also cause an hours-long outage in a small radius.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It could have an immediate effect on transportation infrastructure, as traffic lights and other routing mechanisms as well as ventilation equipment for underground roadways is reliant on electricity.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, infrastructure which relies on the electric grid, including wastewater treatment facilities, the information technology sector, and communications systems could be impacted.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The December 2015 Ukraine power grid cyberattack, the first recorded of its kind, disrupted services to nearly a quarter of a million people by bringing substations offline.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Council on Foreign Relations has noted that states are most likely to be the perpetrators of such an attack as they have access to the resources to carry one out despite the high level of difficulty of doing so.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Cyber intrusions can be used as portions of a larger offensive, military or otherwise.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some security experts warn that this type of event is easily scalable to grids elsewhere.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Insurance company Lloyd's of London has already modeled the outcome of a cyberattack on the Eastern Interconnection, which has the potential to impact 15 states, put 93 million people in the dark, and cost the country's economy anywhere from $243 billion to $1 trillion in various damages.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] House of Representatives Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings, and Emergency Management, the electric grid has already seen a sizable number of cyber intrusions, with two in every five aiming to incapacitate it.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Department of Energy has prioritized research and development to decrease the electric grid's vulnerability to cyberattacks, citing them as an "imminent danger" in its 2017 Quadrennial Energy Review.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Department of Energy has also identified both attack resistance and self-healing as major keys to ensuring that today's smart grid is future-proof.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] While there are regulations already in place, namely the Critical Infrastructure Protection Standards introduced by the North America Electric Reliability Council, a significant number of them are suggestions rather than mandates.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Most electricity generation, transmission, and distribution facilities and equipment are owned by private stakeholders, further complicating the task of assessing adherence to such standards.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, even if utilities want to fully comply, they may find that it is too expensive to do so.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some experts argue that the first step to increasing the cyber defenses of the smart electric grid is completing a comprehensive risk analysis of existing infrastructure, including research of software, hardware, and communication processes.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, as intrusions themselves can provide valuable information, it could be useful to analyze system logs and other records of their nature and timing.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Common weaknesses already identified using such methods by the Department of Homeland Security include poor code quality, improper authentication, and weak firewall rules.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Once this step is completed, some suggest that it makes sense to then complete an analysis of the potential consequences of the aforementioned failures or shortcomings.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This includes both immediate consequences as well as second- and third-order cascading effects on parallel systems.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Finally, risk mitigation solutions, which may include simple remediation of infrastructure inadequacies or novel strategies, can be deployed to address the situation.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some such measures include recoding of control system algorithms to make them more able to resist and recover from cyberattacks or preventive techniques that allow more efficient detection of unusual or unauthorized changes to data.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Strategies to account for human error which can compromise systems include educating those who work in the field to be wary of strange USB drives, which can introduce malware if inserted, even if just to check their contents.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Other solutions include utilizing transmission substations, constrained SCADA networks, policy based data sharing, and attestation for constrained smart meters.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Transmission substations utilize one-time signature authentication technologies and one-way hash chain constructs.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] These constraints have since been remedied with the creation of a fast-signing and verification technology and buffering-free data processing.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] A similar solution has been constructed for constrained SCADA networks.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This involves applying a Hash-Based Message Authentication Code to byte streams, converting the random-error detection available on legacy systems to a mechanism that guarantees data authenticity.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Policy-based data sharing utilizes GPS-clock-synchronized-fine-grain power grid measurements to provide increased grid stability and reliability.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It does this through synchro-phasor requirements that are gathered by PMUs.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Attestation for constrained smart meters faces a slightly different challenge, however.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the biggest issues with attestation for constrained smart meters is that in order to prevent energy theft, and similar attacks, cyber security providers have to make sure that the devices' software is authentic.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] To combat this problem, an architecture for constrained smart networks has been created and implemented at a low level in the embedded system.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The protection system of a smart grid provides grid reliability analysis, failure protection, and security and privacy protection services.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] While the additional communication infrastructure of a smart grid provides additional protective and security mechanisms, it also presents a risk of external attack and internal failures.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Before a utility installs an advanced metering system, or any type of smart system, it must make a business case for the investment.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some components, like the power system stabilizers (PSS) installed on generators are very expensive, require complex integration in the grid's control system, are needed only during emergencies, and are only effective if other suppliers on the network have them.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Without any incentive to install them, power suppliers don't.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Most utilities find it difficult to justify installing a communications infrastructure for a single application (e.g. meter reading).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Because of this, a utility must typically identify several applications that will use the same communications infrastructure – for example, reading a meter, monitoring power quality, remote connection and disconnection of customers, enabling demand response, etc.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Ideally, the communications infrastructure will not only support near-term applications, but unanticipated applications that will arise in the future.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Regulatory or legislative actions can also drive utilities to implement pieces of a smart grid puzzle.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Each utility has a unique set of business, regulatory, and legislative drivers that guide its investments.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This means that each utility will take a different path to creating their smart grid and that different utilities will create smart grids at different adoption rates.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some features of smart grids draw opposition from industries that currently are, or hope to provide similar services.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] An example is competition with cable and DSL Internet providers from broadband over powerline internet access.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Providers of SCADA control systems for grids have intentionally designed proprietary hardware, protocols and software so that they cannot inter-operate with other systems in order to tie its customers to the vendor.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The incorporation of digital communications and computer infrastructure with the grid's existing physical infrastructure poses challenges and inherent vulnerabilities.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] According to *IEEE Security & Privacy*, the smart grid will require that people develop and use large computer and communication infrastructure that supports a greater degree of situational awareness and that allows for more specific command and control operations.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This process is necessary to support major systems such as demand-response wide-area measurement and control, storage and transportation of electricity, and the automation of electric distribution.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Various "smart grid" systems have dual functions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This includes Advanced Metering Infrastructure systems which, when used with various software can be used to detect power theft and by process of elimination, detect where equipment failures have taken place.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] These are in addition to their primary functions of eliminating the need for human meter reading and measuring the time-of-use of electricity.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The worldwide power loss including theft is estimated at two-hundred billion dollars annually.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Electricity theft also represents a major challenge when providing reliable electrical service in developing countries.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The earliest, and one of the largest, example of a smart grid is the Italian system installed by Enel S.p.A. of Italy.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Completed in 2005, the Telegestore project was highly unusual in the utility world because the company designed and manufactured their own meters, acted as their own system integrator, and developed their own system software.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Telegestore project is widely regarded as the first commercial scale use of smart grid technology to the home, and delivers annual savings of 500 million euro at a project cost of 2.1 billion euro.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the largest deployment programs in the world to-date is the U.S.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Dept. of Energy's Smart Grid Program funded by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This program required matching funding from individual utilities.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] A total of over $9 billion in Public/Private funds were invested as part of this program.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This program consisted of Investment Grants (matching), Demonstration Projects, Consumer Acceptance Studies, and Workforce Education Programs.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Reports from all individual utility programs as well as overall impact reports will be completed by the second quarter of 2015.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the U.S., the Energy Policy Act of 2005 and Title XIII of the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 are providing funding to encourage smart grid development.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The objective is to enable utilities to better predict their needs, and in some cases involve consumers in a time-of-use tariff.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Funds have also been allocated to develop more robust energy control technologies.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the US, the city of Austin, Texas, has been working on building its smart grid since 2003, when its utility first replaced 1/3 of its manual meters with smart meters that communicate via a wireless mesh network.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It currently manages 200,000 devices real-time (smart meters, smart thermostats, and sensors across its service area), and expects to be supporting 500,000 devices real-time in 2009 servicing 1 million consumers and 43,000 businesses.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Boulder, Colorado, completed the first phase of its smart grid project in August 2008.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Both systems use the smart meter as a gateway to the home automation network (HAN) that controls smart sockets and devices.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some HAN designers favor decoupling control functions from the meter, out of concern of future mismatches with new standards and technologies available from the fast moving business segment of home electronic devices.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Hydro One, in Ontario, Canada is in the midst of a large-scale Smart Grid initiative, deploying a standards-compliant communications infrastructure from Trilliant.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] By the end of 2010, the system will serve 1.3 million customers in the province of Ontario.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The initiative won the "Best AMR Initiative in North America" award from the Utility Planning Network.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Île d'Yeu began a 2-year pilot program in Spring of 2020.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Twenty-three houses in the Ker Pissot neighborhood and surrounding areas were interconnected with a microgrid that was automated as a smart grid with software from Engie.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Sixty-four solar panels with a peak capacity of 23.7 kW were installed on five houses and a battery with a storage capacity of 15 kWh was installed on one house.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Six houses store excess solar energy in their hot water heaters.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] A dynamic system apportions the energy provided by the solar panels and stored in the battery and hot water heaters to the system of 23 houses.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid software dynamically updates energy supply and demand in 5 minute intervals, deciding whether to pull energy from the battery or from the panels and when to store it in the hot water heaters.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This pilot program was the first such project in France.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The City of Mannheim in Germany is using realtime Broadband Powerline (BPL) communications in its Model City Mannheim "MoMa" project.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Sydney also in Australia, in partnership with the Australian Government implemented the Smart Grid, Smart City program.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It will be possible to control and manage the state of the entire electricity distribution grid at any given instant, allowing suppliers and energy services companies to use this technological platform to offer consumers information and added-value energy products and services.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This project to install an intelligent energy grid places Portugal and EDP at the cutting edge of technological innovation and service provision in Europe.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the so-called *E-Energy* projects several German utilities are creating first nucleolus in six independent model regions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] A technology competition identified this model regions to carry out research and development activities with the main objective to create an "Internet of Energy".
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the first attempted deployments of "smart grid" technologies in the United States was rejected in 2009 by electricity regulators in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, a US state.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This plan was rejected by regulators as it "eroded important protections for low-income customers against shutoffs".
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] According to the Boston Globe, the plan "unfairly targeted low-income customers and circumvented Massachusetts laws meant to help struggling consumers keep the lights on".
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the Netherlands a large-scale project (>5000 connections, >20 partners) was initiated to demonstrate integrated smart grids technologies, services and business cases.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] EPB in Chattanooga, TN is a municipally owned electric utility that started construction of a smart grid in 2008, receiving a $111,567,606 grant from the US DOE in 2009 to expedite construction and implementation (for a total budget of $232,219,350).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Deployment of power-line interrupters (1170 units) was completed in April 2012, and deployment of smart meters (172,079 units) was completed in 2013.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid's backbone fiber-optic system was also used to provide the first gigabit-speed internet connection to residential customers in the US through the Fiber to the Home initiative, and now speeds of up to 10 gigabits per second are available to residents.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid is estimated to have reduced power outages by an average of 60%, saving the city about 60 million dollars annually.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It has also reduced the need for "truck rolls" to scout and troubleshoot faults, resulting in an estimated reduction of 630,000 truck driving miles, and 4.7 million pounds of carbon emissions.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In January 2016, EPB became the first major power distribution system to earn Performance Excellence in Electricity Renewal (PEER) certification.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Certain deployments utilize the OpenADR standard for load shedding and demand reduction during higher demand periods.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid market in China is estimated to be $22.3 billion with a projected growth to $61.4 billion by 2015.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Honeywell is developing a demand response pilot and feasibility study for China with the State Grid Corp. of China using the OpenADR demand response standard.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The State Grid Corp., the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and General Electric intend to work together to develop standards for China's smart grid rollout.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In 2009, the US Department of Energy awarded an $11 million grant to Southern California Edison and Honeywell for a demand response program that automatically turns down energy use during peak hours for participating industrial customers.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Department of Energy awarded an $11.4 million grant to Honeywell to implement the program using the OpenADR standard.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] (HECO) is implementing a two-year pilot project to test the ability of an ADR program to respond to the intermittence of wind power.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Hawaii has a goal to obtain 70 percent of its power from renewable sources by 2030.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] HECO will give customers incentives for reducing power consumption within 10 minutes of a notice.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Part of the IEEE Smart Grid Initiative, IEEE 2030.2 represents an extension of the work aimed at utility storage systems for transmission and distribution networks.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The IEEE P2030 group expects to deliver early 2011 an overarching set of guidelines on smart grid interfaces.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The new guidelines will cover areas including batteries and supercapacitors as well as flywheels.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The group has also spun out a 2030.1 effort drafting guidelines for integrating electric vehicles into the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] IEC TC 57 has created a family of international standards that can be used as part of the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] These standards include IEC 61850 which is an architecture for substation automation, and IEC 61970/61968 – the Common Information Model (CIM).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The CIM provides for common semantics to be used for turning data into information.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] OpenADR is an open-source smart grid communications standard used for demand response applications.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] It is typically used to send information and signals to cause electrical power-using devices to be turned off during periods of higher demand.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak has created a specification that supports distribution functionality of the smart grid.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak has a robust set of integration definitions that supports nearly all of the software interfaces necessary for a distribution utility or for the distribution portion of a vertically integrated utility.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak integration is defined using extensible markup language (XML) and web services.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The IEEE has created a standard to support synchrophasors – C37.118.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] The UCA International User Group discusses and supports real world experience of the standards used in smart grids.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] A utility task group within LonMark International deals with smart grid related issues.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] There is a growing trend towards the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for smart meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] IEEE P2030 is an IEEE project developing a "Draft Guide for Smart Grid Interoperability of Energy Technology and Information Technology Operation with the Electric Power System (EPS), and End-Use Applications and Loads".
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] NIST has included ITU-T G.hn as one of the "Standards Identified for Implementation" for the Smart Grid "for which it believed there was strong stakeholder consensus".
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] G.hn is standard for high-speed communications over power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] OASIS EnergyInterop' – An OASIS technical committee developing XML standards for energy interoperation.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Its starting point is the California OpenADR standard.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] Under the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA), NIST is charged with overseeing the identification and selection of hundreds of standards that will be required to implement the Smart Grid in the U.S.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] These standards will be referred by NIST to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC).
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] This work has begun, and the first standards have already been selected for inclusion in NIST's Smart Grid catalog.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] However, some commentators have suggested that the benefits that could be realized from Smart Grid standardization could be threatened by a growing number of patents that cover Smart Grid architecture and technologies.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] If patents that cover standardized Smart Grid elements are not revealed until technology is broadly distributed throughout the network ("locked-in"), significant disruption could occur when patent holders seek to collect unanticipated rents from large segments of the market.
[src:smart-grid/smart-grid-p02] In November 2017 the non-profit GridWise Alliance along with Clean Edge Inc., a clean energy group, released rankings for all 50 states in their efforts to modernize the electric grid.
